dataIdInfo.idAbs:
This particular feature class contain Rim watersheds, which are the undeveloped mountainous watersheds surround the Central Valley as well as valley watersheds of both Sacramento and San Joaquin valley. The physical hydrology components of CalSim 3 are based on two assumptions for classifying watersheds. The first type of watersheds are those at the foothill and mountainous rim watersheds that surround the Central Valley. These watersheds are relatively undeveloped, and changes in land use over time have not significantly affected the natural outflow from these watersheds. Rim watersheds typically are characterized by complex topography, steep slopes, shallow soils, and limited groundwater aquifer systems. Runoff at higher elevations is largely determined by the snowfall and snowmelt cycle. CalSim 3 represents the hydrology of the rim watersheds as preprocessed time series of unimpaired runoff.
The hydrology of the valley watersheds is simulated using a rainfall-runoff model, soil moisture accounting in the root zone, and a distributed finite element model of the underlying groundwater aquifer.In the valley watersheds, CalSim 3 simulates the movement of both surface water (e.g., storage regulation, stream diversions, and return flows) and groundwater (e.g., groundwater recharge, groundwater pumping, lateral flows, and stream-groundwater interaction).
dataIdInfo.idPurp: The purpose and creation of this data set is to provide CalSim 3 model developers and users the spatial references of the rim and valley watersheds, model boundaries, lakes and reservoirs, water infrastructures, water districts, and regions that represented in CalSim 3 model.This data were collected as a part of developing CalSim 3.0 model.

prcStep.stepDesc:
Rim watersheds were delineated based on DWR CalWater 2.2 watershed definitions modified with custom pour points for CalSim. Rim watersheds based on DWR CalWater 2.2 watershed definitions modified with custom pour points for CalSim 3.0 model. Necessary modifications of the datasets were conducted based on USGS 7.5' Topo Quad contours. Additionally, some watersheds were digitized manually using USGS 1:24,000 topographic maps.
Valley watersheds are subdivided based on Water Budget Areas using NHD HUC-12 watershed definitions modified to pour at specific model nodes. More details will be found in Water Budget Area and Demand Unit Feature class metadata.
